Before the <strong data-start="30" data-end="44">Conclusion</strong>, you can include additional <strong data-start="73" data-end="92">topics/sections</strong> in your seminar paper to make it more detailed and professional. Here’s a suggested structure with extra topics based on your two papers:</p>
<hr data-start="234" data-end="237">
<h2 data-start="239" data-end="291"><strong data-start="242" data-end="291">Suggested Additional Topics Before Conclusion</strong></h2>
<h3 data-start="293" data-end="342"><strong data-start="297" data-end="340">4. Challenges in AI-based Cybersecurity</strong></h3>
<ul data-start="343" data-end="521">
<li data-start="343" data-end="396">
<p data-start="345" data-end="396">False positives and negatives in threat detection</p>
</li>
<li data-start="397" data-end="432">
<p data-start="399" data-end="432">Data privacy and ethical issues</p>
</li>
<li data-start="433" data-end="469">
<p data-start="435" data-end="469">Adversarial attacks on AI models</p>
</li>
<li data-start="470" data-end="521">
<p data-start="472" data-end="521">Scalability and integration with legacy systems</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h3 data-start="523" data-end="566"><strong data-start="527" data-end="564">5. Future Trends and Applications</strong></h3>
<ul data-start="567" data-end="790">
<li data-start="567" data-end="627">
<p data-start="569" data-end="627">AI integration with IoT, blockchain, and cloud computing</p>
</li>
<li data-start="628" data-end="690">
<p data-start="630" data-end="690">Predictive cybersecurity and real-time threat intelligence</p>
</li>
<li data-start="691" data-end="749">
<p data-start="693" data-end="749">Use of generative AI for threat simulation and testing</p>
</li>
<li data-start="750" data-end="790">
<p data-start="752" data-end="790">Autonomous incident response systems</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h3 data-start="792" data-end="832"><strong data-start="796" data-end="830">6. Comparative Table / Figures</strong></h3>
<ul data-start="833" data-end="1040">
<li data-start="833" data-end="958">
<p data-start="835" data-end="958">Side-by-side comparison of algorithms, input datasets, application domains, strengths, and limitations (already prepared)</p>
</li>
<li data-start="959" data-end="1040">
<p data-start="961" data-end="1040">Optional: a flow diagram showing AI threat detection process from both papers</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h3 data-start="1042" data-end="1082"><strong data-start="1046" data-end="1080">7. Key Observations / Insights</strong></h3>
<ul data-start="1083" data-end="1197">
<li data-start="1083" data-end="1118">
<p data-start="1085" data-end="1118">Main takeaways from both papers</p>
</li>
<li data-start="1119" data-end="1157">
<p data-start="1121" data-end="1157">Unique contributions of each study</p>
</li>
<li data-start="1158" data-end="1197">
<p data-start="1160" data-end="1197">Gaps identified for future research</p>
</li>
</ul>
<hr data-start="1199" data-end="1202">
<p data-start="1204" data-end="1283">After these sections, you can then add the <strong data-start="1247" data-end="1261">Conclusion</strong> and <strong data-start="1266" data-end="1280">References</strong>.</p>
<hr data-start="1285" data-end="1288">
<p data-start="1290" data-end="1424">If you want, I can <strong data-start="1309" data-end="1349">now rewrite your Word seminar report</strong> with <strong data-start="1355" data-end="1386">all these sections included</strong> so it’s fully ready for submission.</p>
